      "message": "\u003e (For my edification... why is static needed? For a fixed array, can\u0027t it just generate a bucket of bytes in rodata either way?)\n\nUnfortunately not. C++ (and C) require that addresses of local variables be unique for each call into a function. Where addresses don’t “leak” outside of the function (typically into a callee), the compiler is able to “as-if” optimize this away, because it can see that it’s safe. But in cases like this, there is a “leak” into a callee, and it’s not provably safe, so your pristine rodata is just used as the source side of a memcpy() into a stack buffer. Gross! So you say “static” to avoid that, but of course that’s also a little scary for its own reasons. The “constexpr” keeps it safe and honest. Just “constexpr” alone is safe and honest but not optimize-able.\n\nI spent a day and a half banging my head against this with Leonard this past summer.\n\nThis little surprise is courtesy of the letter C++11 and the numbers 1.8/6 and 1.9/7.\n\nPEE ESS: Clang actually will optimize this by default without the “static”, although it’s intentionally deviating from C++11 in doing so. https://bugs.llvm.org/show_bug.cgi?id\u003d18538. Neither GCC nor MSVC will perform this optimization by default without “static” (and I don’t think Clang should be doing it either).",
